    "summary": "As a scholar-practitioner, I specialize in classical and modern shari`a (Islamic law), Arab tribal laws, rule of law, legal pluralism, Islamic reform, (informal) conflict resolution, constitutional law, the Arab Spring ('madaniya' movement), and human (women\u2019s) rights in the Arab and Muslim world. I have particular expertise in tribal-Muslim societies such as Yemen, Afghanistan, Iraq, but also work on issues related to shari`a and the rule of law in other Arab countries, as well as in Europe.\n\nAfter leading the Rule of Law Unit at UNAMA in Kabul (2007-2009), I started my own bureau Re:Orient and now work as an independent scholar, university lecturer, and advisor to governments and organisations around the world. I am also a regular guest-speaker in the media, public debates, and film festivals, and contribute with my expertise to documentaries and policy development. Additionally, I design programs to generate positive legal and social changes in the MENA-region, and among Muslim communities in the West. Examples are the action-research projects 'Rights at Home' (2001-2005) and the 'Stipulated Marriage Contract Programme (2004-2005).\n\nInspired by the Arab youth in 2011, I designed the action-research programme 'Imagine Madaniya!', which  aims at building a (social, legal, civil) trajectory towards Arab/Muslim 'civil states'. The idea centers around the concept of madaniya (Arabic for civil, civility, civic action, citizenship) as a historically and culturally rooted, yet novel approach to Islam, good governance, rule of law, citizenship, and a new social contract. My enterprise aspires to engage local and trans-national intellectuals and artists, media and decision makers, and the larger public to collectively shape a civil future for the MENA-region.",
